Cathay Pacific, CSR, HSBC, SJM, ZTE: Hong Kong Equities Preview

-- B y   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a
-- 
2011-08-11T01:07:47Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-11/cathay-pacific-csr-hsbc-sjm-zte-hong-kong-equities-preview.html
The following companies may have
significant price changes in  Hong Kong  trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  rose 2.3 percent to 19,783.67. The Hang
Seng  China  Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H shares of
Chinese companies, advanced 1.5 percent to 10,580.41.  Railway-related stocks: China will suspend approvals on new
railway projects and conduct safety checks on all current
projects, the government said on its website.  CSR Corp. (1766 HK), a mainland train maker, declined 0.6
percent to HK$4.75.  China Railway Group Ltd. (390)  (390 HK), a builder
of the nation’s rail link, slid 2.9 percent to HK$2.31.  Hacking attack: Shares of  HSBC Holdings Plc (HSBA)  (5 HK),  Cathay
Pacific Airways Ltd. (293)  (293 HK), Hong Kong Exchanges & Clearing
Ltd. (388 HK), Dah Sing Financial Group (440 HK),  China
Resources Microelectronics Ltd. (597)  (597 HK), Dah Sing Banking Group
Ltd. (2356) and China Power International Development Ltd. (2380)
will resume trading today after being suspended yesterday after
the bourse’s website was hacked, the city’s exchange said.  Huaneng Power International Inc. (902)  (902 HK): The electricity
producer will add 7,000 megawatts of generation capacity this
year and about 5,000 megawatts in 2012, Vice President Lin Gang
said on a conference call. The stock declined 1.2 percent to
HK$3.30.  Semiconductor Manufacturing International Corp. (981)  (981 HK):
China’s biggest chipmaker by market value said it swung to a net
loss of $3.77 million in the second quarter, compared with a $96
million profit in the same period a year earlier. The stock
gained 4 percent to 39.5 Hong Kong cents.  SJM Holdings Ltd. (880)  (880 HK): The casino operator said first-
half profit rose 70 percent to HK$2.67 billion from a year
earlier. The stock advanced 1.5 percent to HK$18.16.  ZTE Corp. (763)  (763 HK): China’s phone-equipment maker said in a
preliminary earnings statement its first-half net income fell 12
percent from a year earlier to 768.5 million yuan. The stock
jumped 5 percent to HK$21.15.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Kana Nishizawa in Hong Kong at 
 knishizawa5@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle at 
 ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 